Loved it...first time there and want to go back. Was there Tues., Wed, and Thurs.
Impressions:
1. Many dealers had items priced at what I would consider &quot;show prices&quot;...I took a
quick look at those tables and kept
walking. (I saw the 'Roses 25 Cents' letters too...cool, but expensive!)
2. Found some great items at low prices; had to work to find them, but well worth
it. (Example: 2 books that I bought for $5 each list at $125 each on Bibliofind.)
3. Don't like the concept of no-setup-til-the-gate-opens. Since I flew out there,
was buying smalls. There was no point being
there when gates opened as dealers couldn't get totally unpacked for quite awhile.
4. Took quite a bit of cash, (much more than I normally would carry), but when
that ran out found a lot of resistance to Traveler's Checks. I pointed out to some
dealers that they are far more likely to get burned by counterfeit $20 bills
(common
where I live). I wasn't trying to clean their change out either; this was for say
a $48 item paid for with a $50 traveler's check.
5. Met interesting people. We stayed in a B&amp;B where there was a couple from
England, (advanced collectors of miniature
sewing machines), an edge-tool collector from Colorado, and a mining collector from
Delaware among others.
6. New collection started: Shaker Sewing kits and other old sewing/needlework
items.
7. Want to take a truck next time I go and bring back furniture. Lots more nice
old primitives than I find around here.
8. Don't like the truckloads of European primitives and sap buckets that people
were scarfing up.
9. Missed my snoring husband. Traveled with my mother. She's 72 years old and
hums a lot. (Love her anyway!)

Jan

